\section{Greeting}{


A greeting is an optional welcome message shown before any conversation
messages. It is automatically dismissed when the user sends their first
message (unless created with \code{dismissible = FALSE}).

\strong{Static greeting.} Pass a string or \code{\link[=chat_greeting]{chat_greeting()}} to the \code{greeting}
parameter:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{chat_ui("chat", greeting = "## Hello!\\n\\nHow can I help you today?")
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

\strong{Dynamic greeting from the server.} Leave \code{greeting} unset and use
\code{\link[=chat_set_greeting]{chat_set_greeting()}} from your server function. This is useful when the
greeting depends on session state or is generated by a model.

\strong{\code{greeting_requested} input.} When the chat is visible on the page, has
no messages, and has no greeting set, Shiny fires
\verb{input$<id>_greeting_requested} (e.g. \code{input$chat_greeting_requested} for
\code{chat_ui("chat")}). The value is an event counter suitable for
\code{\link[shiny:observeEvent]{shiny::observeEvent()}}. Use it to trigger server-side greeting generation:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{observeEvent(input$chat_greeting_requested, \{
  stream <- chat_client$stream_async("Generate a short welcome message.")
  chat_set_greeting("chat", chat_greeting(stream))
\})
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

This input fires when the chat component is first viewed on the page and
empty, and again after \code{\link[=chat_clear]{chat_clear()}} \code{(greeting = TRUE)}, enabling a
regenerate pattern where clearing the greeting automatically triggers a
fresh one.

\strong{\code{greeting_dismissed} input.} When the user dismisses the greeting,
\verb{input$<id>_greeting_dismissed} fires with a \code{Date.now()} timestamp. If the
greeting is later cleared after being dismissed, the input resets to \code{NULL}.
If you use \code{\link[=chat_mod_server]{chat_mod_server()}}, you can access the \code{greeting_dismissed}
reactive from the returned module value instead of the raw namespaced input
string.
}

\section{Thinking display}{


When a model produces reasoning or "thinking" tokens, shinychat renders them
in a collapsible panel above the response. The panel shows a live stream of
the model's reasoning while it thinks, then auto-collapses when the response
begins.

Thinking display works automatically with any model that supports it. Two
paths are supported:
\enumerate{
\item \strong{ellmer's \code{ContentThinking} objects.} Models that provide a structured
thinking API (e.g., Claude with extended thinking) emit \code{ContentThinking}
objects when you stream with \code{stream = "content"}. shinychat detects these
and routes them to the thinking panel. This is what \code{chat_append()} uses
internally when you pass it an ellmer content stream.
\item \strong{Raw \verb{<thinking>} tags.} Many open-source and local models (DeepSeek,
QwQ, Qwen, etc.) emit \verb{<thinking>...</thinking>} tags directly in their
markdown output. shinychat detects these tags during streaming and renders
the enclosed text in the thinking panel with no extra configuration.
}
\subsection{Topic labels}{

You can optionally get labeled sub-sections within the thinking panel by
asking the model to emit \verb{<topic>...</topic>} tags in its reasoning. These
are extracted and rendered as section headings inside the thinking display,
and the current topic appears in the collapsed header as a live status.

To use topic labels, add something like this to your system prompt:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode">}}\preformatted{When thinking through a problem, wrap brief topic labels in <topic> tags
to indicate what you're currently reasoning about. For example:
<topic>parsing the input</topic>
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}

Topic labels are entirely optional. Without them, the thinking panel still
works -- it just won't have sub-section headings.
}
}

